  "pride_metadata": {
    "project": {
      "accession": "PXD052379",
      "title": "Anti-proteolytic regulation of KRAS by USP9X/NDRG3 in KRAS-driven cancer development",
      "additionalAttributes": [],
      "projectDescription": "Cancers with activating mutations of KRAS show a high prevalence and poor prognosis but remain intractable, requiring innovative strategies to overcome the poor targetability of KRAS. Here, we report that KRAS expression was post-translationally up-regulated through the deubiquitination of KRAS protein when the scaffolding function of NDRG3 (N-Myc downstream regulated gene 3) promoted specific interaction between KRAS and a deubiquitinating enzyme, USP9X. In KRAS-mutant pancreatic or lung cancer cells KRAS protein expression, downstream signaling, and cell growth were highly dependent on NDRG3. In conditional KrasG12D knock-in mouse models of pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma (PDAC), Ndrg3 depletion abolished Kras protein expression in pancreas, and suppressed pancreatic intraepithelial neoplasia (PanIN) formation. Mechanistically, KRAS protein bound to the C-terminal serine/threonine-rich region of NDRG3, subsequently going through the deubiquitination by USP9X recruited to the complex. This interaction could be disrupted in a dominant-negative manner by a C-terminal NDRG3 fragment that can bind KRAS but is defective in USP9X binding, highly suppressing the KRAS protein expression and KRAS-driven cell growth. In summary, KRAS-driven cancer development critically depends on the deubiquitination of KRAS protein mediated by USP9X/NDRG3, and KRAS-addicted cancers could be effectively targeted by inhibiting the KRAS-NDRG3 interaction.",
      "sampleProcessingProtocol": "For IP-Mass analysis, Flag-NDRG3 were transfected into MIA PaCa-2 cells. After 48 hours incubation, serum was starved for 12 hours, and then serum or EGF were treated for 4 hours. After that, cells were harvested and lysed with RIPA lysis buffer, and then the lysates were immunoprecipitated with pre-washed FLAG M2\u00ae affinity gel (Sigma-Aldrich) for overnight incubation at 4 \u00b0C. Next, the beads were washed 3 times with RIPA lysis buffer, and the bound proteins were rapidly detached from the beads by adding 1X SDS elution buffer and heating at 100 \u00b0C for 5 minutes. Detached proteins were used for analyzing MS/MS-based phosphor-peptide identification.  Filter-aided sample preparation method was used for the digestion of proteins with trypsin. Briefly, proteins were reduced with 10mM dithiothreitol at 37 \u2103 for 30 min, and UA buffer (8 M urea, 100 mM Tris-HCl) was added to a final volume 400 \u03bcL. After activation of Amicon 30k centrifugal ultrafiltration units (Merck) using UA buffer, samples were loaded into the filters and washed with the UA buffer 3 times. Proteins were then alkylated by 50 mM iodoacetamide in UA buffer in the dark at room temperature for 30 min. Filter units were washed with the UA buffer and then with the ABC buffer (50 mM ammonium bicarbonate), 3 times respectively. Samples were then digested with trypsin in ABC buffer at 37 \u2103 for 18h, and the resulting peptides were eluted by adding ABC buffer. The collected eluates were dried with centrifugal vacuum concentrator (Labconco). Peptides were purified using Sep-Pak C18 Cartridge (Waters) and were again dried in a centrifugal vacuum concentrator (Labconco).  High-Select Fe-NTA Phosphopeptide Enrichment Kit (Thermo Fisher Scientific) was used to enrich phosphopeptides according to the manufacturer\u2019s instruction with some modification. Briefly, peptide samples were suspended in Binding/Wash buffer (0.1% trifluoroacetic acid, 50% acetonitrile), and columns were washed with the Binding/Wash buffer 3 times. Samples were loaded into the columns and incubated for 30min at room temperature. Columns were washed 3 times with the Binding/Wash buffer and then with water 1 time. Phosphopeptides were eluted with 0.5% ammonium hydroxide and were dried in centrifugal vacuum concentrator (Labconco).",
      "dataProcessingProtocol": "Samples were resuspended in 0.1% formic acid and were analyzed using Agilent 1100 Series high-performance liquid chromatography (HPLC) pump (Agilent Technologies) coupled to Finnigan LTQ linear ion trap mass spectrometer (Thermo Fisher Scientific). Peptide separation was conducted on a homemade C18 fused silica column (100 \u03bcm internal diameter) with nano-electrospray ionization interface. Split flow configuration was used for adjustment of column flow rate to ~250 nL/min. Solvent A (0.1% formic acid) and B (0.1% formic acid, 80% acetonitrile) were used for 1h gradient, and peptides were eluted with the following gradient: 0-40% B for 50 minutes, 40-100% B for 5 minutes, 100% B (20-21 min), and 100% B for 5 minutes. MS survey scan across 450-2000 m/z was acquired in data-dependent mode and positive ion mode with a spray voltage of 2.1 kV. The top 10 most abundant ions in each MS scan were selected for the MS/MS scan with normalized collision energy of 35%. Dynamic exclusion was set as 30 s to avoid analyzing the same abundant precursor ion.  Raw files were searched against UniProtKB/Swiss-Prot human database (release 2017_11) containing 150,510 sequence with SEQUEST HT algorithm in Proteome Discoverer Software (ver. 2.2; Thermo Fisher Scientific). For protein identification, precursor and fragment mass tolerance were set to 3.0 Da and 1.0 Da, respectively. Full-tryptic peptides were searched with a maximum of two missed cleavages. Fixed modification included carbamidomethyl cysteine (+57 Da), and variable modifications included oxidation of methionine (+16 Da) and phosphorylation of serine, threonine, and tyrosine (+80 Da). False discovery rate (FDR) was determined using the target-decoy strategy coupled to Percolator (q-value < 0.01), and only peptide spectral match meeting the FDR less than 1% was accepted.",
